<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-28T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-28T03:00:00-05:00" n="592" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d592">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/14316: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-28T15:00:00+07:00">August 28,
                                1943—3 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received 8 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1585. To Rosenthal, OEW, from Fowler: Department’s 1178, August 23. Smuggling
                        situation being currently investigated by us. Morris now quietly conducting
                        investigation. I will forward complete details on both antimony and tungsten
                        as soon as he reports. Although Chinese insist smuggled tungsten does not
                        exceed 2 to 300 tons a year, that much larger amounts are handled is
                        indicated by other sources of information. [Fowler.]</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>